 @G[c3 stills_73.png]@L 
		@H Historical Background @L
		Rome's first forays into Britain were under Gaius Julius Caesar during the Gallic Wars. On two separate occasions, he led a sizable expedition at the head of his legions. @L@L
		Romans were intrigued by the rumors of gold laying openly on the beaches and immense riches for the taking in Brittania. This proved false, however. The invasion force was opposed right from the start. The Romans had to conduct a contested amphibious landing at the cliffs of Dover, where Briton tribes gathered an army for battle. @L@L
		After a hard battle, Romans established their camps and found out that local villages were impoverished. Caesar's expedition had to retreat later due to supply difficulties and the fact he could not abandon Gaul for long for fear of a revolt. @L@L Britons, much like the Gauls, were a group of separate tribes, each ruling over their own territory. @L@L
		In a second attempt, Rome defeated the Briton coalition which formed to oppose them and made allies and established client states. This would not last long, however, as Romans would not return to the island until 43 AD under Emperor Claudius. It was then when the Britons were finally brought under full Roman rule and large-scale colonization began. @L@L
		Londinium was one of the biggest cities in Roman Britain and was founded at the site of an old Roman military camp. Even though the tribes were defeated, trouble would still be on the horizon for Romans in Britain, as mistreatment from the local armies would lead to widespread unrest. @L@L
		To the north lay the land of Caledonia, inhabited by the Pictish people who were fiercely independent. The terrain and guerilla tactics would see Rome abandon the effort to try and subjugate them and instead they later built one of the largest fortifications in the ancient world, Hadrian's Wall. @L@L
		
		@G[c3 instructions icon.png]
		@H Instructions @L
		Governor, you are to travel to Britannia. For a provincial capital, Rome requires a large and prosperous city on the main island. The area selected for this task is on the banks of a large river, with plentiful clay and timber both for trade and for local construction projects. However, as it is far away from the rest of the empire, luxury goods and especially oil will be a challenge to import in large quantities. @L@L
		You must establish an economy of scale, building a large city with mass production of pottery and furniture to export in bulk to other cities in Gaul and to fledgling colonies in Britain. Prices may be low, but the quantities of these goods demanded are immense. @L@L
		Londinium is in a good position to establish itself as a major trade hub and support many cities with its exports. Though they are not available locally, if you import iron and vines, you could also expand into exports of weapons and wine. @L@L
		If that was not enough of a challenge: I, Caesar, have decreed that taxes levied on Roman citizens in Britannia will remain low, to encourage colonists moving in to support our efforts; so do keep this in mind. @L@L
		Lastly, I will take a moment to discuss military matters. Peace reigns in the Roman Empire and in the new province of Britannia, even though it remains a frontier province full of freshly subjugated peoples. @L@L
		Despite the many peaceful Britons and the lack of any official wars, some local peoples remain hostile. Manage your legions well, governor, for they might be needed in the future, even if only as a deterrent against unrest. @L@L
		
