		@H Historical Background @L
		Ancient Britons would use tactics and equipment like the Celts, Gauls and to some extent, the Germans. Most of the armies would be made up of light infantry and skirmishers. Briton nobles preferred to use the chariot, however, which was mainly popular during the Bronze Age in other parts of the world. @L@L
		Chariots would be used as a platform from which javelins would be thrown and it would goad enemies into breaking formation. In melee, chariots could charge but usually would dismount and fight as elite infantry to prevent damage to the chariot itself. @L@L
		Most cultures abandoned the use of chariots for several reasons. Its high production and upkeep cost was one, and they could be too easily countered by massed skirmishers. Additionally, chariots required very flat land to operate, and battlefields often had obstacles, natural or man-made, on them thus keeping them out of certain areas. @L@L@L@L

